#regex-builders

-rxe {
Uses method chaining with readable names like .digit(), .one_or_more(), .literal(). Great for building complex patterns piece by piece. Patterns can be saved and reused as variables.
```python
email = (rxe
    .exactly(username)
    .literal('@')
    .exactly(domain)
)
```
Install: pip install git+git://github.com/mtrencseni/rxe
}

-python-VerbalExpressions {
Python port of the popular VerbalExpressions family. Very readable fluent API with methods like .start_of_line(), .find(), .maybe(). Best for simpler patterns where extreme readability matters. Wide language support across many platforms.
```python
url = (VerEx()
    .find('http')
    .maybe('s')
    .find('://')
)
```
}

-regex-builder {
Functional approach with immutable builder objects. Good for systematic construction with functions like literal(), range(), repeats(). Allows pattern reuse and composition. Less actively maintained than the others.
```python
number = optional(range('1-2')).range('0-9')
```
}

-regal {
Uses Clojure data structures (vectors and keywords) to represent regex patterns, similar to Hiccup for HTML. Supports multiple regex flavors (Java, JavaScript) and can generate test data from patterns.
```clojure
(def r [:cat
        [:+ [:class [\a \z]]]
        "="
        [:+ [:not \=]]])
(regal/regex r)
;;=> #"[a-z]+\Q=\E[^=]+"
```
}

